Finished last night. Probably Gene Wolfe's most "engineer prose" book, would appeal to STEMcel bros, very indulgent in Naval engineering details, historical piracy lore, etc. Type of book you'd ideally read next to an Atlas map and with Wikipedia open on the other web browser tab

You could tell he just really enjoyed reading a bunch of maritime history textbooks and very old first hand stuff and putting it together into a novel. Probably not the best book to start with Gene Wolfe overall (BoTNS is better) but very enjoyable to read and also a standalone.

One of my personal etiquette rules is never showing people anything on my phone while we are together. No memes, no funny videos or wiki articles. I can message them to the person when I get home. But it is an honor for anyone to wish to share something he found curious with you.

Psychiatrists check on patients staying at home to see if they're stable or having/about to have an acute episode of mental illness by asking them how their sleep has been lately. Usually patients have a few nights of bad sleep or insomnia before a new episode of mental disorder.

You can tell sticking ur phone into someone's face to show them something is wrong. It's like blowing smoke into their face. It feels clunky and awkward. Forces them to exaggerate their reaction to it or pretend to find it funny. But this is not intuitive to many good-hearted ppl

It's obviously a very complex relationship with a chart that has a lot of arrows between the different stuff and there's obviously no need to spook yourself if you can't get any good sleep for a few days, it happens to most people. But good mental health and sleep do go together.

One pretty reasonable answer to "What actually happened to Hitler after WW2?" that's not him escaping to the 5D hollow earth but no one seems to ever propose for some reason is the British just sent him into exile in isolation like they did with Napoleon after they defeated him.

Another example is Wilhelm II, the British allowed him to go into exile instead of having him dead and told the Dutch not to hand him over to anyone. Part of the English colonial mentality. Once you're not a threat they put you into a safe home and let you live your life out.
I guess he was an actual danger and also refused to resign etc. and there's the Hessian aspect

Saw some guy who said his wife had PCOS and problems with fertility and her doctor recommended Ozempic and it turned out she was actually obese but he still thought it was a bad idea. I feel like people are getting influenced by memes, it's obvious obesity is bad for fertility...

Like Ray Peat repeatedly talked about too much starch/flour and high dietary fat leading to obesity (which is also why he recommended low fat milk to people), moderately restricting calories until you go down to a normal weight range will obviously be a good idea for most people.

If you're hypothyroid it's obviously going to be harder to lose weight and you should probably be on thyroid medication but still obesity is very bad for health and going to a normal BMI if possible is absolutely a good idea if you don't just starve yourself or do anything crazy.

People find most political speeches uninspiring and boring because they take them at face value while they're actually very much an "esoteric" form and the real message of a speech is meant to be understood by a small number of people in the know who will hear it and understand.

E.g. Most important speech of Churchill's career was actually after the end of WW2 and after he was no longer prime minister, 1946 in the USA in Missouri. Fulton speech was the British elite's offer to the US to split the world between the two Empires. Anglo-American cooperation.
